Political Games: Endnotes

These illustrations are suggested in the endnotes of Political Games.

1 Getting Going

First open R or Rstudio and install the hop package from github:

devtools::install_github("macartan/hop")

Then load it up:

library(hop)

2 Implement

Some normal form games: PD (#1), with and without equilibrium marked

payoffs <-  matrix(c(2,3,0,1),2)
gt_bimatrix(payoffs, labels1=c("C","D"))

gt_bimatrix(payoffs, labels1=c("C","D"), nash=FALSE, arrow1=FALSE)

Chicken (#2): Pure strategy equiibriums marked

payoffs <- matrix(c(2,3,1,0),2)
gt_bimatrix(payoffs, labels1=c("C","D"))

Assurance (#3): Pure strategy equiibriums marked

payoffs <- matrix(c(3,2,0,1),2)
gt_bimatrix(payoffs, labels1=c("C","D"))

Illustrating the folk theorems (#4), for the Prisoner’s Dilemma:

gt_folkmm(matrix(c(2,3,0,1),2))

…and for the Assurance Game

gt_folkmm(matrix(c(3,2,0,1),2))

Condorcet Jury (#10): Gives an illustration of the law of large numbers

gt_jury(n=7, base=.6)

Power indices (#13): Shows mapping between raw votes and power for two seemingly similar committees

gt_plot_banzhaf(c(1, 1, 3,7,9,9)/30,.5)

gt_plot_banzhaf(c(1, 1, 3,7,9,10)/30,.6)

Plott (#14): Illustrating the absence of stable points

gt_majority_phase(matrix(c(0, 0, .5, 1, 1, 0), 2))

gt_majority_phase(matrix(c(.2, .2, .5, .9, 1, 0), 2),
                  raylengths=c(.5, .2))

Cycles (#15): Majority rule cycling

gt_cycles(3, 25)

Legislative bargaining (#18): Returns equilibrium returns given recognition probabilities

gt_leg_barg(c(.8,.2,0))
## [1] "Anything goes: one of multiple equilibria selected"
## [1] "allocations: 0.796, 0.199, 0.005"

Cascades (#22): Where you end up after 50,000 random orderings

x <- c(1,1,1,1,1,1,0,0,0)
D <- replicate(50000, gt_declarations(sample(x))$Declarations)
mean(D[9,])
## [1] 0.89284

Nash bargaining (#27)

gt_nbs(u1 = function(x) x^.5, u2 = function (x) 1 - x)

Simple version with equilibrium only marked.

gt_nbs(solution_only = TRUE)

Two Coase theorem illustrations (#31)

gt_coase(X=matrix(c(2,3,0,1),2), matrix=TRUE, feasible=TRUE,
         bargain = TRUE)

gt_coase(f=function(x) 1-x^2, matrix=FALSE, feasible=TRUE,
           bargain = TRUE, SQ=c(0,1))

Clake-Groves mechanism (#36). The circular indifference curves at the bottom right imply dominant strategies

gt_cgm (theta1 = .2, theta2 = .4)

Meltzer Richard (#40): Attitudes to taxes for a given endowment

gt_plot_mr (e = .5, main = "Endowment = 0.5")

Evolutionary stabilty (#47)

gt_sss (e = 0, t = 2)

Nash’s theorem illustration (best response functions) (#A3)

XC <- matrix(c(0,1,.75,.25),2)
gt_bimatrix(-XC, XC, srt1=90,
            labels1=c("Left","Right"), P1="Goalie", P2="Shooter")

The best response graph – you can do one of these for any normal form game. In this case you can see that if the shooter plays left with probability 0.33, the goalie is willing to play any srtategy (solid vertical line at 0.33); if the goalie plays left with probability 0.5, the shooter is willing to play any srtategy (horizontal dotted line at 0.5).

gt_brgraph(-XC, XC,
           labelsR=c("Left", "Right"), PR="Goalie", PC="Shooter")
